<br>
It does actually. Even better, a process like this may (eventually) lead to a source of small scale, relativly safe, atomic energy that one would be able to switch on and off at will.<br>
<br>
Yale, the reactor-reprocessing-bomb route is only one of the many ways of acquiring a WMD. It is by no means the best one if you are trying to build a clandestine one. Proliferation is, to my mind, more of a social and political problem, rather than merely a technical one <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  At the end of the day, any state that really wants the Bomb can build one! Nothing short of pre-emtive attack/invasion will prevent them. And of course, by dooing that you only make the case stronger for WMD aquisition <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Tim, Though I don't know how it works. Either the experiment worked or it didnt. Now the results were either successful, faked (Not unheard of in science, sadly) or there was a process going on that wasnt fully understood but appeared to give the right result (Like with the cold fusion experimnents)Nevertheless, I don't really see any fundamental reason why the process shouldn't work.<br>
<br>
We are all familiar with a process that turns stable and mildly unstable nuclei into unstable (induced radioactivity)  or extremely unstable (Fission) ones by exiting them with just the right amount of energy. I accept this is normally done with neutrons. But why *not* finely tuned laser beams hitting just the right resonant frequency?<br>
<br>
Indeed, if you can do it once, you can do it better. Concievably one may be able to use this system to induce fission in U238 providing a safe, non-critical source of Atomic energy that does not require the production of Plutonium or enriched Urainium. (or the construction of reprocessing facilities for that matter)<br>
<br>
