 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 234<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/9/03 6:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=938.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Better 'laser', than never..   ;)</span><hr size=1> Yale. I accept that dual use technologies are the most popular manufacturing route by the established weapons states. I also accept that once you have the reactor-reprocessing-reactor cycle in place the possibility of diverting material to a weapons programme is almost trivially easy.<br>
<br>
However this is not a process that can be done easily in secret and the facilities are vulnerable to attack (e.g. the Israeli attack on the Iraqi reactor complex)<br>
<br>
To my mind, any rogue state (or even a wealthy private individual, there are plenty out there that could afford it!) that wanted to develop Nukes *in-secret* would go down the enrichment route rather than the rather more obvious reactor route.<br>
<br>
For a *rogue-state* (N Korea, Iran etc?) to go down the, blindingly obvious, reactor-reprocessing-bomb route is, To my mind, perhaps, more about politics than weapons. <br>
<br>
Ultimately the issue of proliferation can be summed up by paraphrasing a quote from the letters page of new scientist (it was referring to gun control and columbine/dunblane etc) <br>
<br>
The problem of nuclear proliferation is not about the comparatively trivial *HOW* but the desperate *WHY*!<br>
<br>
We cannot put this particular genie back in its bottle. The knowledge and technology is already too widely known.<br>
<br>
Proliferation is a political problem not a technical one.<br>
<br>
To borrow another catchphrase.<br>
<br>
&quot;Reactors don't make bombs, people make bombs&quot;<br>
<br>
