<br>
Enrichment centrifuges are simple in concept, a bear in practice. (Iraq was never able to get them to work) They use VERY high technology, the materials of which scream &quot;dual-use&quot;. It is also a larger scale project than Pu239 production. Pakistan has somewhere near 14,000 centrifuges to feed its tiny program.<br>
<br>
Mining and extraction of uranium whether from dirt or seawater is a LARGE project.<br>
<br>
You missed my point. The U238 (or thorium232) to reactor to spent fuel to reprocess to bomb fab is ONE route.<br>
<br>
Uranium to enrichment to bomb fab is another.<br>
<br>
I very specifically pointed out that ANY - ANY- possession, manipulation, training, or ANY connection whatsoever with actinide material - whether uranium ore, critical assemblies, nuclear engineering schools, research reactors, centrifuge facilities - whatever - is unambiguously and irretreivably MILITARY. No games like the UK built its Magnox fleet as &quot;civillian&quot; power plants, all the while extracting the Pu239 for its weapons program.<br>
<br>
Declaring that ANY nuclear activity is military, does not, by itself prevent proliferation. It simply removes the ambiguity that is the basis for the entire industry and spread of materials, financing and infrastructure.<br>
<br>
The political costs to a proliferator easily become too high when it is absolute and undeniable that their actions are warlike. Buy a ton of yellowcake - then you are building weapons. Produce a ton of yellowcake - then you are sourcing a proliferators weapons program. Train a nuclear engineer - you have a latent weapons program. <br>
<br>
The countries may continue on its path, but it must directly face the international consequences.<br>
<br>
At this very moment Iran is using the &quot;civillian&quot; cover to continue its atomic weapons program. Under an international policy of considering ANY and ALL nuclear related activities INHERENTLY and UNAVOIDABLY of military utility (which is of course true) then Iran and Russia would be held to infinitely more severe pressure.<br>
The same would hold true for China/Korea, France/Iraq, Russia/India, etc. No games, no ploys, no carefully nurtured confusion. Simply arming with an atomic stockpile.<br>
<br>
BS treaties like the NPT would be recognized as the worthless rag they are. Suppliers of nuclear grade zirconium would have no place to hide. and so on<br>
<br>
-------------------------------------------<br>
As Ted Taylor pointed out, except for some very small uses, like medical isotopes, etc (which is easily supplied by a handful of internationally managed TRIGAs) all nuclear technologies are simply (and much more economically) replaceable by non-violence-capable alternatives.<br>
<br>
<br>
-------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Your motto is better stated as:<br>
&quot;Reactors don't build bombs,  people with reactors build bombs&quot;<br>
<br>
Or as Edward Teller, the &quot;father&quot; of the H-Bomb said:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I wish I could be as optimistic and positive about the remaining objection: as nuclear reactors spread among nations their production will enable almost every country to acquire nuclear weapons.  This statement, most unfortunately, is true.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Or as Lovin's said, paraphrasing the saying &quot;A chicken is one eggs way to make another egg&quot;:<br>
<br>
&quot;A reactor is a bomb's way to make another bomb&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
